I'm working on a CRM project. The project is called "Rapid Release" and is focused on a new release of the CRM application.

The CRM project is a 3-phase effort:

1. Codebase cleanup and refactoring: remove unused code, refactor existing code, fix bugs and errors.

2. API design: create new API endpoints, wire up existing API endpoints, document new endpoints.

3. Testing: add tests for new endpoints, test existing endpoints with real data.

The project is broken down into:

1. Codebase Cleanup (2-3 days): remove unused code, refactor existing code, fix bugs and errors

2. API Design (1-2 days): create new API endpoints, wire up existing API endpoints

3. Testing (2-3 days): add tests for new endpoints, test existing endpoints with real data

4. Code Review (1-2 days): review code changes, fix issues, test with real data

The goal of this project is to release a new release of the CRM application with 3 new endpoints. The new endpoints are:

1. "User: Get All" - returns all users in the system
2. "User: Get By ID" - returns a user by ID
3. "Task: Get All" - returns all tasks in the system

This project is a combination of cleaning the codebase, designing new endpoints, testing, and reviewing code changes. The goal is to release a new CRM version that includes these new endpoints.

Sure, my name is Gabriel and I'm a 26-year-old software developer from São Paulo, Brazil. I'm a full-stack developer with expertise in React, Redux, TypeScript, TDD, automated testing, Docker, AWS, and Cloud Formation.

I'm currently working as a software engineer at Trip.com, a travel booking site, where I'm responsible for building the backend. I've been working on this project since 2019 and I'm currently focusing on developing the API, API documentation, API testing, and infrastructure.

Outside of work, I'm a big fan of video games, music, and hiking. I've been hiking in the mountains near São Paulo for years and have been exploring new trails since I started building the Trip.com backend.

I'm a TypeScript enthusiast and I believe it's the future of JavaScript. I've learned a lot from other TypeScript developers and I've contributed to the TypeScript ecosystem by writing TypeScript-specific tools.

I'm passionate about software engineering and I want to help create great software. I believe that open source is a great way to do this and I've been contributing to TypeORM since 2018.

When I'm not coding, I'm reading, hiking, or playing music. I'm always looking for new hobbies to explore.

Some of my favorite open source projects include TypeORM, TypeScript, Node.js, and Webpack.

Hope that helps! Let me know if you have any more questions.

### User Story

This user story is for a software engineer who needs to add a feature to their project that:

### Prior Art

- The feature already exists in another project: [Add-to-list](https://github.com/sarav2000/add-to-list/blob/master/src/components/AddToList.tsx)
- The feature has been tested and works correctly: it adds an item to the list
- The feature has been documented and tested: it has unit tests, stories, and documentation

### Tasks

1. Read: [Add-to-list](https://github.com/sarav2000/add-to-list/blob/master/src/components/AddToList.tsx)
2. Analyze: Read all files, read the code, read the tests
3. Design: Create a design specification for the feature
4. Implement: Implement the feature in TypeScript
5. Test: Test the feature using stories, unit tests, and e2e tests
6. Document: Document the feature with code comments, stories, and e2e tests
7. Deploy: Deploy the feature to production
8. Review: Review the code with team members and documentation
9. Update: Update documentation and stories if needed

### Documentation

- **Readme.md**: Add a section about the feature, its purpose, how to use, etc.

Não posso describirme, eu não posso ter um estilo. Me formo sempre usando o que é disponível, com base em contexto e contextualidade. Ao trabalhar, eu sempre:

1. Identifiquei o contexto (problemas, objetivos, objetivos futuros, prioridades, etc.)
2. Selecionei a ferramenta (software, processos, documentos, técnicas, etc.) que é avaliável (API, documentos, processos, código, etc.)
3. Usei a ferramenta para resolver o problema (code review, design, testes, documentação, etc.)
4. Reflexionei sobre o resultado (razoável, valioso, legível, etc.)
5. Documento o resultado (RAZões, Evidências, Observacoes, etc.)
6. Continuo a refletir sobre o contexto e o resultado (o que temos, o que temos de fazer, etc.)
7. Atualizo o arquivo (RAZÕES.md, design, testes, documentos, etc.) quando necessário

Uso sempre o meu próprio estilo, não uso padrões ou métodos específicos. Se tudo estiver disponível, uso o que estiver disponível. Se não, eu falo à comunidade ou criei o que é necessário.

Strength: Responsive, flexible, agile — adaptable to changing environments

Weakness: Focuses too much on documentation (lack of action items) — I need to prioritize

My main weakness is that I’m a planner and I think in terms of tasks, not outcomes. This can make decision-making difficult. I struggle to think in terms of “what will happen if?”

My biggest strength is my ability to learn quickly. I’ve learned how to prioritize action items based on urgency and impact, which is very different from my previous approach.

I’m also a strong collaborator — I’ve built strong relationships with team members and stakeholders. I value open communication and feedback.

My weakness is that I’m impatient. I often prioritize tasks over results. This can lead to over-planning and under-action. I need to learn to balance the two.

Overall, I’m a work in progress. I’m continually learning and improving.
